e of the most important public policy issues in the United States is how to improve the life prospects of disadvantaged youth who, in their formative years, face low-quality school systems, poor access to health care, and high-crime environments. The Problems of Disadvantaged Youth includes a broad range of research examining various aspects of disadvantage, and ways of increasing the ability of low-income youths to improve their circumstances later in life. Taking an empirical economics perspective, the nine essays in this volume assess the causal impacts of disadvantage on youth outcomes, and how policy interventions can alleviate those impacts. Each chapter develops a framework to describe the relationship between youths and later life outcomes, addressing such factors as educational opportunity, health, neighborhood crime rates, and employment. This vital book documents the serious short- and long-term negative consequences of childhood disadvantage and provides nuanced evidence of the impact of public policy designed to help needy children.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPoor youthxEducationzUnited States. 0aPoor youthxHealth and hygienezUnited States. 0aPoor youthzUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  ayouth, poverty, inner city, juvenile, delinquency, at risk, education, health care, access, crime, neighborhood, community, low income, class, economics, policy, government, nonfiction, educational opportunity, employment, children, pre-kindergarten participation, elementary schools, school lotteries, compulsory schooling, school-leaving laws, human capital, obesity, early childbearing, teen pregnancy, social organizations, religion, violence.1 aAizer, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Patricia M., econtributor